+This Django project lives entirely under `apps/project-tracker/` and uses SQLite plus server-rendered HTML with vanilla JavaScript.
+
+## Prerequisites
+
+- Python 3
+- `pip`
+
+If Django is not installed in your local environment yet, Django commands in this workspace currently fail with:
+
+```text
+ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'django'
+```
+
+That error is an environment/setup issue, not a tracker application defect.
+
+## Create a local virtual environment
+
+From the repository root:
+
+```bash
+python3 -m venv .venv
+source .venv/bin/activate
+python3 -m pip install --upgrade pip
+python3 -m pip install django
+```
+
+## Apply migrations
+
+From the repository root:
+
+```bash
+python3 apps/project-tracker/manage.py migrate
+```
+
+The default database is SQLite at `apps/project-tracker/db.sqlite3`.
+
+## Run the development server
+
+From the repository root:
+
+```bash
+python3 apps/project-tracker/manage.py runserver
+```
+
+Open the local URL shown by Django, typically `http://127.0.0.1:8000/`.
+
+## Focused verification commands
+
+Run the Python syntax check used in this workspace:
+
+```bash
+python3 -m py_compile $(find apps/project-tracker -name '*.py' | sort)
+```
+
+Run the focused Django test modules used for the tracker app:
+
+```bash
+python3 apps/project-tracker/manage.py test tracker.tests.test_domain tracker.tests.test_views
+```
+
+If the test command still raises `ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'django'`, install Django in the active environment first and rerun the command.

